Sparse channel estimation is a fundamental problem in wireless communications, where multipath channels exhibit sparse impulse responses with only a few significant taps. Traditional greedy algorithms such as Orthogonal Matching Pursuit (OMP) and convex relaxation methods like LASSO achieve reasonable performance but suffer from high computational complexity or suboptimal recovery quality. In this paper, we investigate the application of the Learned Iterative Shrinkage-Thresholding Algorithm (LISTA)---a deep-unfolded architecture originally proposed for sparse coding---to sparse channel estimation. By unrolling ISTA iterations into a fixed-depth neural network with learnable step sizes, thresholds, and linear mappings, LISTA adapts to channel statistics through end-to-end training without requiring explicit sparsity knowledge. We provide a systematic analysis of LISTA's behavior in the channel estimation context, including ablation studies, generalization experiments, and practical deployment tests. Under matched distribution conditions (i.i.d.~Gaussian channels), LISTA achieves $\sim$$-0.05$~dB NMSE, outperforming properly tuned OMP ($\sim$3~dB) and LASSO ($\sim$3~dB). The ablation study reveals statistically significant but quantitatively modest component contributions (learnable mapping $\sim$0.006~dB, $p = 0.006$; learnable threshold $\sim$0.016~dB, $p = 0.006$), with the overall optimization pipeline being the primary source of improvement. Generalization within the training distribution is robust across sparsity and SNR levels. However, LISTA fails on realistic ITU channel models when trained on i.i.d.~Gaussian data, while OMP and LASSO achieve $-26$ to $-28$~dB, highlighting a critical distribution sensitivity that can be addressed by distribution-matched training or hybrid LISTA/OMP deployment. The optimal network depth is 5--8 layers, with $0.47$~ms CPU inference and $32{,}784$ parameters. These findings provide a practical framework for deploying deep unfolding in sparse channel estimation, identifying both strengths and actionable mitigation strategies for its limitations.
